# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: copenhagen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:copenhagen/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Folketing elections were held in Denmark on 23 March 1943 alongside Landsting elections, except in the Faroe Islands where they were held on 3 May.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] They were the only parliamentary elections held during the German occupation, and although many people feared how the Germans might react, they took place peacefully.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Nazi Germany permitted the election to proceed and had consistently maintained that Denmark was still an independent country.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] They had also reportedly provided substantial financial support for the Danish National Socialist Workers' Party.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] The five democratic parties (Social Democrats, Conservatives, Venstre, Social Liberal and the Justice Party) urged voters to support any of them.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] The Communist Party had been banned since 1941 and could not participate in the elections.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] 95% of the vote went to the four largest traditional democratic parties and the Social Democratic Party remained the largest in the Folketing, winning 66 of the 149 seats.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Voter turnout was 89% in mainland Denmark, the highest of any Danish parliamentary election, and became a demonstration against the occupation.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Leading German newspapers expressed disappointment and indignation with the lack of political evolution among the Danish voters.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] In Denmark there has been some debate about whether this can be seen as democratic support for the government's "cooperation" policy (*samarbejdspolitikken*) with the German occupation authorities.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Some have argued that the result showed a broad unity of opinion in the population and among politicians in support of the relatively cooperative line taken by the government.
[src:copenhagen/1943-danish-folketing-election] Bertel Haarder, citing Knud Kristensen, has argued that the vote was sold as one of solidarity with the Danish constitution, democracy, and a rejection of totalitarian elements in society, and cannot therefore be seen as an explicit endorsement by the population of the government's line.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] The **2011 UCI Road World Championships** took place in Copenhagen, Denmark, over 19–25 September 2011.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] The event consisted of a cycling road race and a time trial for men, women, men under 23, and for the first time since 2004 the junior men and junior women competed at the same event as the elite riders.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] It was the 78th running of the Road World Championships.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] Castelfidardo near Loreto in Italy was also a candidate, but Italy held the UCI Road World Championships in Varese in 2008.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] It was the first time that Denmark has hosted the event since 1956, when it was also held in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] Cyclists from 71 national federations participated.
[src:copenhagen/2011-uci-road-world-championships] The number of cyclists per nation that competed is shown in parentheses.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] On 3 July 2022, a man opened fire at the Field's shopping mall in Copenhagen, Denmark, killing three people and critically wounding four others.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The perpetrator, 22-year-old Noah Esbensen, was arrested after the shooting; he had a history of contact with the psychiatric healthcare system He was charged with three murders and seven attempted murders, but was later found innocent by reason of insanity.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The mass shooting was the first in Denmark since a gang-related shooting in the same city in 2016.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Earlier in the day, Esbensen took a subway to the Field's shopping mall to socialize in anticipation for a visit from his brother.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He walked around the mall and called his brother at 14:11 before leaving.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He considered buying a ticket to watch a movie, but purchased nothing.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] In his apartment, the shooter decided to shoot up the mall as a last-minute decision.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] At 16:58, Esbensen reentered the mall through an external staircase to the mall's movie theater on the second floor while carrying a shoulder-bag and case containing magazines, his father's rifle, a handgun, a knife, clothing, earbuds, and sunglasses.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He walked into the theater's restroom and sat in the toilet stall.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] While in the toilet stall, Esbensen started loading his weapons and changed his clothes.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He also got on his phone to look at social media, and to look up suspected serial killer Wayne Williams and a guitar shop.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] When he tried loading the handgun, he wasn't able to get it to work due to overloading the weapon.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] At 17:14, while in the toilet stall, he started a call to a psychiatrist's office.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] However, he was only met with an automated message.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He stayed silent on the other end for 16 minutes before hanging up.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Immediately afterwards, he opened his YouTube app and started playing his "killer music" playlist.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He put on his earbuds and left the restroom at 17:32:56, leaving behind one magazine for his rifle and the Walther P1 handgun on the floor of the toilet stall.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Immediately after leaving the restroom, Esbensen aimed at a 47-year-old Russian man with his two sons.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He fired two shots at the man, hitting his left flank and right shoulder.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A 17-year-old male employee stepped into the theater lobby to investigate the gunshots.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen fired a shot at him, wounding the teen.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter walked up to the injured teen and fired one more shot point-blank into his head, killing him.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter lowered his rifle briefly before raising it to aim at an Afghan man, who was at a counter looking to buy candy for his daughter before watching Minions: The Rise of Gru with his family.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter walked up close to the man before firing a shot, hitting the man's right shoulder.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The man collapsed and crawled towards his distressed family.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter unloads his magazine and replaced it with a new one before running out of the theater and into the main mall.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] As the shooter ran north, he came across a woman in front of him and started chasing her.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He repeatedly pulled the trigger only for no shots to fire due to an empty casing being in the gun.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter stopped running and worked the bolt-action of the rifle to discharge the casing and load in a new bullet.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He turned west and started chasing two girls while screaming.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] As he was running, he came across a crowd of 20 more people running away from him.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He fired a single shot at them and missed.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen eventually reached the mall's escalators, where several mallgoers were running down, and fired a single shot at the top.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shot hit a woman in the leg and shattered the glass.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen fired another shot towards the top of the escalators, hitting the same woman in the shoulder and injuring another woman in the lower back.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] At some point, the escalators stopped causing several people to fall to the bottom of the escalator, including the injured.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen turned around and fired a shot at a woman in front of the Calvin Klein who just got out of the escalators.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The bullet hit the woman before entering the body of another woman in front of her, injuring both.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen turned back to the escalators and fired a shot at the people laying down.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He killed a 17-year-old teenage girl while injuring another person with the same shot.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] After he reloaded, the shooter shouted that no one in the mall were real and that "it's not real".
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A 13-year-old boy who was laying in the bottom of the escalators responded to the perpetrator by telling him that he was real and begged him not to shoot.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The perpetrator said that he was not real again, before the boy told him that he was real a second time.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The perpetrator let out a scream and ran up the escalators, sparing everyone.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter reached the third floor of the mall where the food court is.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He fired a shot down the hall hitting no one.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A Swedish man who was looking for his family was walking near the sushi restaurant unaware of the shooter.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen fired a shot at him, hitting him in the stomach.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The man briefly fell before walking out of the mall.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen fired two more shots, one hitting a window and another hitting the restroom/KFC area, hitting no one.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] On the third floor, a man recorded Esbensen shouting and shouldering the rifle, before running away while screaming.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen discharged a live round and loaded a new magazine to his rifle.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen ran down the same escalators he shot people on and ran out of the mall through an emergency exit at the back of the second floor.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He walked down the emergency stairwell and fired a final shot outside the mall, hitting no one.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter continued through the parking lot and finally stopped in front of a road.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He got down to his knees and took out his cellphone.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He proceeded to call his mother to apologize to her.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The shooter wasn't able to recall most of the conversation, but cellphone data confirmed the call lasted a minute.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] While on the phone, police arrived to arrest Esbensen.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Esbensen refused to listen to the police's commands and shouted at them to kill him while still carrying the phone.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Eventually, the police got him to lay down after pepper spraying him and handcuffed him.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Police received the first shooting reports at 17:37 at the Field's shopping mall located in Ørestad, a developing city area on Amager in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A man carrying a rifle, a pistol and a knife – which was not used in the attack – had entered the mall sometime before 17:30.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A witness said the shooter seemed violent and angry, running and shouting.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] When directly addressed by the witness, the shooter said that "it is not real".
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The rifle caliber has been speculated as either 6.5×55mm or .308 Winchester/7.62×51mm.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] According to police, the victims appear to have been random, with no indication that any particular group was targeted.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The suspect was arrested by police eleven minutes after the shooting had been reported.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Three people were killed, and four more were seriously wounded by gunfire.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The dead are a 17-year-old Danish girl, a 17-year-old Danish boy and a 47-year-old Russian man who was living in Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Another 23 people received minor injuries, including three whose injuries were from stray gunfire, with the additional twenty individuals injured in the evacuation.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The four seriously wounded victims are two Swedish citizens and two Danes.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A 22-year-old Danish man, later named as Noah Esbensen, was arrested in connection with the shooting.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Born in 2000, Esbensen had a history of contact with the psychiatric healthcare system.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] When he started being under psychiatric care, he was diagnosed with schizophrenia and psychosis.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He was given antipsychotics to treat the condition.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] However, psychiatric officials later ignored that diagnosis and treated him for autism.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] They lessened his dosage in the months leading up to the shooting.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Months before the shooting, he had gained an interest in serial killers and mass shooters, citing Randy Stair, the perpetrator of the Eaton Township Weis Markets shooting, as one of his inspirations and claimed his videos "opened his eyes".
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He even disclosed this information to his psychiatrists.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] There was also evidence that Esbensen originally planned to shoot up a kindergarten near his apartment.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Weeks before the shooting, Esbensen recorded two videos of himself talking about how he suffered from suicidal thoughts and his hatred for society.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He would leave those two videos in a USB drive found in his apartment.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He also left behind handwritten notes about killing people along with a floorplan and schedule of the kindergarten he planned to shoot up.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] At the trial, he explained that he thought the people he shot were «zombies».
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A day before going to the mall, he uploaded videos on his Youtube channel where he simulated suicide with the rifle and pistol, and said that a specific type of psychiatric medication did not work.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] He also uploaded images of himself pretending to be dead with fake blood leaking out of his mouth two days before the shooting.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] When he entered the mall, he went directly to the restroom, and tried to get help from a suicide lifeline for 16 minutes, in vain.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] This was due to the lifeline not being active in the summer vacation, but they didn't close the line, resulting in callers being put in a non-existent line.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The firearms he used during the shooting and posed with in the videos were not owned by him and he did not have the required firearms license.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] They were legally owned by Esbensen's father, who was a member of a sport shooting club and was living in the same home as the shooter.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] In the videos posted by the shooter before the attack, a gun safe can be seen.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The accused has been charged with three murders and seven attempted murders.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] At a court hearing on 4 July 2022, he was remanded to a closed psychiatric unit.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Prior to starting the hearing, the judge asked the media to leave the court room and held the hearing behind closed doors, with the accused remaining in custody until 28 July.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The court banned the release of the victims' names.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] The defendant's trial began on 12 June 2023.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] On 5 July, the defendant was found insane and sentenced to detention in a secure medical facility.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A temporary crisis center where people could receive psychiatric help was opened after the shooting.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Shortly after the shooting, the Danish royal family announced that a reception due to be hosted by Crown Prince Frederik to celebrate Denmark hosting the 2022 Tour de France had been cancelled.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] British singer Harry Styles cancelled a concert at the nearby Royal Arena scheduled later that evening.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] A memorial held on 5 July 2022 at the Field's shopping mall was attended by thousands of people, the Prime Minister of Denmark Mette Frederiksen, Lord Mayor of Copenhagen Sophie Hæstorp Andersen, other senior political figures as well as Crown Prince Frederik and Prince Christian of Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] An additional tribute to the victims, in the form of a minute's silence, was observed at the Tour de France before the start of the fourth stage of the race on 5 July.
[src:copenhagen/2022-copenhagen-mall-shooting] Prime Minister Frederiksen described the attack as cruel, said that she had the deepest sympathy with the victims and their families, and thanked the police and first aiders.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk's business activities include port operation, supply chain management, warehousing and air freight.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company is based in Copenhagen, Denmark, with subsidiaries and offices across 130 countries and over 100,000 employees worldwide in 2024.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] It is a publicly traded family business, as the company is controlled by the namesake Møller family through holding companies.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company's 2025 annual revenue was US$53.9 billion.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller - Maersk announced its strategic choice to separate its oil and gas-related operations from the conglomerate structure and to concentrate only on container logistics in 2016.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The majority shareholding in Maersk Tankers was sold to A.P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Oil was sold to TOTAL S.A. in 2018, and Maersk Drilling became a separately listed company in April 2019.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2017, the company was one of the main victims of the NotPetya ransom malware attack, which severely disrupted its operation for several months.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2021, the company bought 8 carbon-neutral ships for £1bn.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August 2021, Maersk joined the BEC Low-Carbon Charter.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In September 2023, Maersk unveiled Laura Mærsk, which uses methanol as a fuel.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Laura Mærsk is a feeder vessel of 2,100 TEU capacity in service on the Baltic Sea.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In June 2023, Maersk also announced an order for six additional mid-sized container vessels of 9,000 TEU capacity.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In November 2023, Maersk signed an agreement with Chinese developer Goldwind.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The agreement looks to secure annual volumes of 500KT of fuels including bio-methanol and e-methanol produced utilising wind energy at a new production facility in Hinggan League, Northeast China, around 1000km northeast of Beijing.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The first volumes are expected to arrive in 2026.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The Maersk logo is a white, seven-pointed star on a pale blue background.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The blue of the background came to be known as "Maersk blue", when it was trademarked by the company after the purchase of their first ship in 1886.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] According to a story recounted by Captain P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Møller's son Mærsk Mc-Kinney Møller, the logo dates back to 1886 when it was used on the captain's first steamer, SS *Laura*.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The story relates an episode where Captain Møller's wife, Anna, had accompanied him on a sea voyage and fallen seriously ill.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] When The Steamship Company Svendborg was founded in 1904, the seven-pointed star on the pale blue background became its funnel emblem and the company's house flag symbol.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] When The Steamship Company of 1912 was established, the seven-pointed star was also chosen as their logo.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The white seven-pointed star has represented Maersk throughout the years, with only minor changes.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The most recent changes date back to 1973 when Maersk enlisted the Danish designer and architect Acton Bjørn to establish a more modern design, which is still used today.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller–Maersk by revenue and staff (around 25,000 employees in 2012) is Maersk Line.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2013, the company described itself as the world's largest overseas cargo carrier and operated over 600 vessels with 3.8 million twenty-foot equivalent unit (TEU) container capacity.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] As of January 2021, as the largest container fleet, it held 17% of the global TEU.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2006, the largest container ship in the world to that date, the E-class vessel *Emma Maersk*, was delivered to Maersk Line from Odense Steel Shipyard.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Since then, seven other sister ships have been built, and on 21 February 2011 Maersk ordered ten even larger container ships from Daewoo, the Triple E class, each with a capacity of 18,000 containers.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] There was an option for 10–20 more, and in June 2011, Maersk placed a follow-on order for a second batch of ten sister ships (to the same design with the same shipyard), but cancelled its option for a third batch of ten.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] As of February 2010, Maersk had an order book for new ships totaling 857000TEU (including options on the Triple E class); that backlog is larger than the existing fleet of the fourth-largest line, Evergreen Line.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Line cooperated with the United States Navy on testing 7–100% algae biofuel on the Maersk Kalmar in December 2011.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In January 2012, Søren Skou took over as CEO of Maersk Line from Eivind Kolding.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Later that year, the company ceased its business in Iran in order to prevent potential damage to the company's business with Western countries, particularly the US, due to the sanctions regime led by those countries.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Uggla was appointed Chair of the Board at A.P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller – Maersk, succeeding Jim Hagemann Snabe.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The appointment marks a generational change in the company.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Uggla represents the founding family and remains as CEO of A.P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 12 December 2022, Vincent Clerc was appointed CEO of Maersk effective 1 January 2023.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Svitzer was founded as a salvage client in 1833 before entering the towing business in 1870.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Svitzer became majority owned by Maersk in 1979.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Svitzer has continued to grow, including through purchasing the tugboat operations of Adsteam, and it now has a fleet of over 400 tugs, line handlers and other vessels.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company provides harbour and terminal towage services in over 100 ports and 20 oil and gas terminals across the globe.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In January 2022, Svitzer operated a fleet of 110 vessels in seven ports and 11 terminals across 12 countries in Svitzer operates in the Africa, Middle East & Asia regions.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In February 2024, Maersk's Board of Directors demerged APMM's Svitzer's towage and marine services operations.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] APMM transferred shares of Svitzer A/S and its subsidiaries, along with related assets and liabilities, to a newly created entity named Svitzer Group A/S.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The shares of Svitzer Group were subsequently listed on Nasdaq Copenhagen A/S.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The distribution of Svitzer Group shares to APMM shareholders was agreed at an exceptional general meeting.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] As a result, APMM's shareholders received shares in Svitzer Group in addition to their existing APMM holdings.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Trading of Svitzer Group shares on Nasdaq Copenhagen began on 30 April 2024.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Damco was the combined brand of the Maersk Group's logistics activities, previously known as Maersk Logistics and Damco.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] As of 2008, Damco had 10,800 employees in offices in more than 93 countries. and was involved in supply chain management and freight forwarding all over the world.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In September 2019, Maersk announced that they would dissolve the Damco brand and integrate their remaining activities after initially merging Maersk Line and Damco at the beginning of 2019, when the freight forwarding business of Damco stayed separate.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The dissolving of the Damco brand was completed by the end of 2020.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In the 2025 financial year, Maersk generated revenue of US$53.9 billion.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] During the same financial year, 108,160 employees worked for the group.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Oil (Danish: Mærsk Olie og Gas A/S) was established in 1962 when Maersk was awarded a concession for oil and gas exploration and production in the Danish sector of the North Sea.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Oil is engaged in exploring and producing oil and gas in many parts of the world.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Total oil production is more than 600,000 barrels per day (95,000 m³/d) and gas production is up to some 1 billion cubic feet (28,000,000 m³) per day.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Most of this production is from the North Sea, from both the Danish and British sectors, but there is also production in offshore Qatar, Algeria and Kazakhstan.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In addition to the above-mentioned producing sites, Maersk Oil is involved in exploration activities in Danish, British, Dutch and Norwegian sectors of the North Sea, Qatar, Algeria, Kazakhstan, Angola, Gulf of Mexico (US sector), Turkmenistan, Oman, Morocco, Brazil, Colombia and Suriname.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Most of these activities are not 100% owned but are via membership in a consortium.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company developed production techniques for complex environments (The North Sea, etc.) and drilling techniques that extract oil from problematic underground conditions.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller–Maersk with 22% of its revenue and 68% of its profit in 2008.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Møller - Mærsk A/S announced the signing of an agreement to sell Mærsk Olie og Gas A/S to Total S.A. for US$7.45 billion in a combined share and debt transaction.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The transaction was subject to regulatory and competition approval and was closed on 8 March 2018, when Maersk Oil became a part of Total.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Drilling supports global oil and gas production by providing high-efficiency drilling services to oil companies worldwide.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company owns 24 rigs and its fleet consists of six Ultra-Harsh jack-ups, four XL Enhanced jack-ups (including one new build which is set for delivery in late 2016), four Harsh jack-ups, two Premium jack-up, four semi-submersibles and four Ultra deepwater drillships.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Drilling is, among others, a market leader in the Norwegian jack-up market with a market share of 7 out of 12 rigs As of 2016.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Drilling merged with Noble Corporation in 2022, the transaction was completed on 3 October.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Supply Service provides anchor handling, towage of drilling rigs and platforms, and supply service to the offshore industry.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] By 2021, the fleet consisted of 41 vessels, including anchor handling tug supply vessels (AHTS), subsea support vessels (SSV) and platform supply vessels (PSV).
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In July 2024, it was announced that Norway's DOF Group would acquire Maersk Supply Service for approximately $1.1 billion to consolidate its offshore service sector further, focusing on the oil and gas sector.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Line, Limited (MLL) is a US-based subsidiary of A.P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller–Maersk Group, which owns and operates a fleet of US-flag vessels providing the U.S.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Federal Government and their contractors with multimodal transportation and logistics services.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] A Virginia-based organization, MLL manages the world's largest fleet of internationally traded US-flagged vessels.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The Red Sea crisis had a significant impact on shipping, from November 2023 onward; in May 2024, Maersk estimated the impact as a capacity loss of 15–20 percent across the merchant shipping industry, based on its FY second quarter.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] MCC Transport hosts containerized cargo services in the intra-Asia market.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company was later renamed Sealand-Asia.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Seago Line is a subsidiary shipping line which serves ports in the Mediterranean region.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company is now Sealand- Europe and Mediterranean.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Safmarine is an independently operated shipping company in the A.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Moller–Maersk Group with roots in Africa.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] It operates a fleet of over 40 container vessels and 20 multi-purpose vessels (MPVs).
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company has five container vessels and four MPVs on order for delivery in 2009–2011.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In September 2020, it was announced that the Safmarine brand would be integrated into Maersk.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] SeaLand, branded "Sealand – A Maersk Company", is an American regional maritime and logistics operator.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The Sealand name was phased out in 2009, but revived as a separate brand in 2014.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] After focussing on intermodal services between North, Central and South America, in 2018 it was merged with other Maersk intra-regional brands MCC Transport and Seago Lines to cover European, Mediterranean, and Intra-Asian markets.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2023 it was decided to unify the Maersk brands and integrate the Sealand brand into Maersk.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Over the course of 2023 all Sealand business was integrated with Maersk, and in December 2023 the Sealand brand ceased to exist.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk GSC operates shared service centres that handle back office and off-shore activities for AP Moller Maersk Group.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] GSCs are in Chennai, Mumbai, Pune, Bengaluru, Chengdu, and Metro Manila, with new GSCs to be opened in Mexico and Brazil to support Americas customers.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August of 2025, Maersk inaugurated a new shared service centre in Warsaw, Poland, to support its European customers.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Tankers, offshore and other shipping activities" accounted for 8.8% of Maersk's revenue in 2008 and posted 25% of the group's profit for this period.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The business segment comprises Maersk Tankers (its technical management business sold to Synergy Marine Group in 2021), Maersk Supply Service, Maersk Drilling, Maersk FPSOs, Maersk LNG and Svitzer.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Brazilian coaster container ship subsidiary with eight ships.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In January 2024, it was announced that Hapag-Lloyd, together with Maersk, would launch a long-term operational cooperation under the name Gemini Cooperation in February 2025.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The new cooperation is expected to comprise around 340 ships with a combined capacity of 3.7 million standard containers (TEU); of these, Maersk is to provide 60% and Hapag-Lloyd 40%.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Ardent Salvage, a joint-operating salvage company formed after the merger between Maersk-operated Svitzer and Crowley-operated TITAN Salvage, is involved in towage, salvage, wreck removal, marine firefighting and other offshore support and is represented in more than 100 ports worldwide.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Acquired in 2020, KGH is a European customs and trade solutions provider, including customs broker services and software application development.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The KGH brand is now migrated into Maersk Customs Services.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company formerly owned a stake in Dansk Supermarked Group which operates stores under the brands: Bilka (hypermarket), Føtex (supermarket, department store), Salling (department store) and Netto (discount supermarket).
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Training provides specialist training to specific industries.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The 2010 merger of Maersk Training Centre and Svitzer Safety Services broadened a portfolio of courses to include the maritime, oil and gas terminals, and wind power industries.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] With Headquarters in Svendborg, the MT Group global locations include Aberdeen and Newcastle in the UK, Esbjerg in Denmark, Stavanger in Norway, Rio de Janeiro in Brazil, Chennai & Mumbai in India, Kuala Lumpur in Malaysia.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] New centres include Houston, United States and Dubai, United Arab Emirates which is also the Middle Eastern hub.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In October 2023, Maersk Training bought the Norwegian company ResQ, a supplier of safety training and emergency preparedness.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Star Air operated 11 leased Boeing 767 cargo aircraft, primarily engaged in long-term contract flying for United Parcel Service (UPS) in Europe.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The Maersk corporate aircraft, a Gulfstream 450, was also operated by Star Air.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August 2022, Star Air became part of Maersk Air Cargo.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2023 Maersk announced the inaugural flight of a new air freight service with scheduled flights between Billund, Denmark (BLL) and Hangzhou, China (HGH) - the first scheduled air cargo operation between Denmark and Asia.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The Eurasia operation began 20 March with three weekly flights on the first of three newly converted Boeing 767-300 freighters that were recently added to the fleet of Maersk Air Cargo.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In July 2024, Maersk took delivery of the first of two new Boeing 777F aircraft, which it will operate on its route from Billund to Hangzhou.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August 2013, Freightliner Group announced the acquisition of a leading European intermodal rail operator and railway undertaking, ERS Railways B.V., from Maersk Line.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] ERS Railways B.V. is a railway transport company headquartered in Rotterdam that provides cargo transport, mostly ISO shipping containers.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] World Robot Olympiad is a robotic competition headquartered in Singapore.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Oil is currently a Gold sponsor of this event.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Møller-Maersk company accounts for over 80% of the Danish top 30 companies' emissions of carbon dioxide from operations.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Mærsk has increased emissions by 2% since 2019, with a total of 37 million tonnes in 2021.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company presented plans to be CO2 neutral by 2040.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Since the Danish climate targets of a 70% CO2 reduction in 2030 are territorial based, emissions from foreign shipping and aviation from Danish ports and airports, and internationally, are not counted, as the responsibility lies with the UN's organizations for aviation (ICAO) and shipping (IMO).
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] However, IMO has committed to halving the industry's greenhouse-gas emissions by 2050, and because 80% of global trade (around 11 billion tonnes) is transported by sea each year, global shipping generated about 1,000 million tonnes (3%) of carbon dioxide emissions in 2018.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] "*These are figures that are publicly available.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] But they have probably not really come to light because shipping has been totally unregulated.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] But when the biggest ships sail out, you have to imagine that 50 million cars will follow,"* says Jørn Winkler, founder of DK Group.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] For example, there are filters that remove virtually all sulfur dioxide and nitrogen, but the price of a filter for a large container ship is DKK 25 million.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Environmentalist organizations however believe that the shipping companies have installed scrubbers on their ships so that they can continue to sail on cheap heavy bunker oil, which contains many environmentally harmful substances.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2023, Maersk became the first in the shipping industry to have its 2030 and 2040 targets validated by the Science Based Targets initiative (SBTi) in alignment with a 1.5°C and net zero pathway under SBTi's new maritime industry guidance.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] These new targets include specific sub-targets for scope 1, 2 and 3 emissions and will replace previous targets announced in early 2022.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Denmark is the world's 11th largest flag state based on gross tonnage (the indication of a ship's size, ed.) in 2022, and the shipping companies account for approximately one-fifth of Denmark's total exports.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] According to the industry association Danish shipping, the latest figure for Danish-flagged ships is 779 ships with a total tonnage of 23.24 million gross registered tonnes, out of more than 50,000 merchant ships that trade internationally, under the flags of 150 nations.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Shipping companies in Denmark have a unique tax scheme – tonnage tax, which has been in force since 2001 to keep the shipping companies on Danish soil.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Tonnage tax means that shipping companies pay a fixed tax or charge per ship, and the amount is thus not affected by the company's profit.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] With the tonnage tax, the shipping companies avoid the classic corporation tax of 22 per cent, which other companies must pay.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] But DKK 80 billion is calculated on its way to the shareholders of Maersk, where 45.23 percent is owned by 82,000 different shareholders in Denmark and abroad.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] This compared to a deficit of DKK 3 billion in the company's accounts for the first half of 2009. – The first deficit in the group's history since World War II, with an expected deficit for the whole of 2009 of DKK 10.7 billion.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] These meetings happened even though Maersk said publicly that they were open to paying more taxes if it happened through a global agreement.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] A strategy defended by the Social Democratic Minister for Taxation in 2023, 'Nothing abnormal' in that they have opposed global minimum tax.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On the morning of 8 April 2009, the 17,000-ton *Maersk Alabama* was en route to Mombasa, Kenya, when it was hijacked by pirates off the Somali coast.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The company confirmed that the US-flagged vessel had 20 US nationals on board.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] This was the first time that the US had to deal with a situation in which Americans were aboard a ship seized by pirates in over 200 years.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] By noon, the Americans could resist the pirates and regain control of the boat.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] However, the pirates retreated on a covered lifeboat and held the captain hostage for four days.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 12 April 2009, it was confirmed that the captain held hostage was freed by the US Navy, whose SEAL sharpshooters killed three of the pirates.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] A fourth pirate surrendered earlier due to a medical injury.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] These events were subsequently dramatized in the 2013 film *Captain Phillips*, directed by Paul Greengrass, starring Tom Hanks in the titular role.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Some crew members were involved in the development of the film as well.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk Line estimated that piracy costs the company $100 million per year due to longer routes and higher speed, particularly near East Africa.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] As of 2010, all 83 Maersk tankers were diverting around the Cape of Good Hope south of Africa instead of going through the Suez Canal, although *Mærsk Mc-Kinney Møller*, the first of the Triple E-class vessels, successfully navigated the Suez during her maiden voyage.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Frequent attacks by Houthi rebels in the Suez Canal during the 2020s also kept Maersk vessels from shipping through the Red Sea, only returning in January 2026, with successive successful trans-Suez crossings by *Maersk Sebarok* and *Maersk Denve*r.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Trade unions and labor rights organizations have criticized Maersk's labor practices in different parts of the world.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In El Salvador, Maersk has been accused of maintaining abusive conditions for port drivers.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Charges include excessively long shifts, minimal wages and the repression of freedom of association by running union-busting campaigns, including firing and blacklisting at least 100 drivers in 2001.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Globalization Monitor, a labor rights group based in Hong Kong, has reported poor labor conditions in Maersk facilities in Dongguan and Qingdao, China.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In January and May 2008, two riots reportedly broke out amongst workers at the Maersk plant in Dongguan in protest of poor working conditions and employment terms.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In response to a complaint from whistleblower Jerry H.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Brown II, the US Government filed suit against Maersk for overcharging for shipments to US forces fighting in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In a settlement announced on 3 January 2012, the company agreed to pay $31.9 million in fines and interest but made no admission of wrongdoing.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Brown was entitled to $3.6 million of the settlement.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August 2010, the US government fined Maersk $3.1 million for violating its embargo on Sudan.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The US government imposed a trade embargo on Sudan in 1997 due to human rights violations linked to the civil war between the north and south of the African country and also because of the regime's alleged support of international terrorist groups.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In July 2010, Maersk had ties to an Iranian company that was blacklisted by the EU, Tidewater Middle East Co.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The firm suspended operations at several Iranian ports owned by Tidewater Middle East Co after being pressured by the United States government.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk operates in other Bangladeshi ports and also diverted shipments to Dubai, partnering with other Bangladeshi companies that are not bound by U.S. sanctions.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 28 April 2015, the Marshall Islands-flagged container ship *Maersk Tigris*, which was not owned by Maersk, was travelling westbound through the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Iranian Revolutionary Guard naval patrol boats contacted the ship and directed it to proceed into Iranian territorial waters, according to a spokesman for the US Defense Department.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] When the ship's master declined, one of the Iranian craft fired shots across the bridge of *Maersk Tigris*.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The master complied and proceeded into Iranian waters near Larak Island.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The US Navy sent aircraft and a destroyer, USS *Farragut*, to monitor the situation.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Maersk stated they have agreed to pay an Iranian company $163,000 over a dispute about ten container boxes transported to Dubai in 2005.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The court ruling allegedly ordered a fine of $3.6 million.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In October 2010, Maersk plead guilty to 8 counts of failing to provide adequate hours of rest and 1 count of failing to improve the situation.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In February 2014, Maersk paid 8.7 million to settle allegations that Maersk had forged documents on a contract to ship cargo to Afghanistan.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The government says they uncovered 277 instances "in which claims verifying receipt of shipments in Afghanistan contained forged signatures." The settlement included no admission of guilt.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In May 2021, a Maersk officer's license was suspended after he was accused of sexual assault, including abusive, unwanted, and inappropriate touching in violation of Maersk's anti-harassment policy.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 12 October 2021, Maersk suspended five employees for their involvement in the rape of a 19-year-old girl.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In June 2022, Hope Hicks, formerly known as "Midshipman X" filed a lawsuit against Maersk, alleging that the company failed to protect her from rampant sexual abuse.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In the same month, a second US Merchant Marine Academy (USMMA) student under the alias "Midshipman Y" filed a suit against Maersk, also alleging that the company did not protect her from sexual abuse and violence.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In 2009, it was estimated that the Maersk fleet's use of bunker fuel released sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxides, into the atmosphere corresponding to the emissions from 9 billion cars, with resultant serious health, environmental, and climate change impacts related.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Health problems linked to nitrogen oxides are linked back to a study in 2023 that found nitrogen oxides to be a major contributor to the bone deterioration in postmenopausal women.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The study included a cohort of 161,808 postmenopausal women, with approximately one in two of involved women experiencing a bone fracture or damage to the lumbar spine as a result of exposure to the emissions.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] For example, lumbar spine bone mineral density (BMD) decreased 0.026 g/cm2/year per a 10% increase in 3-year mean NO2 concentration, or the amount to 1.22% annual reductions, nearly double the annual effects of age on any of the anatomical sites evaluated.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Ivan Seistrup, group vice-president in A.P.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Møller Mærsk, stated in 2009: "Among other things, we have entered into close cooperation with Boeing on the development of biofuel for the shipping industry, which will constitute a technological quantum leap.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The two most common types of biofuel are bioethanol and biodiesel.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In August 2024, the South African Government was alerted to two Maersk chartered ships (*Campton* and *Candor)* carrying approximately 816 total metric tonnes on board the two ships in 100 short containers of toxic steel furnace dust collected from pollution control filters.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The containers were collected from Albania to be delivered to Thailand, passing around the south of Africa on route.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The containers in question that potentially could contain mis-declared/hazardous waste cargo were picked up by Maersk (on behalf of MSC) in Trieste and were to be unloaded in Singapore.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The practice, known as cloaking, can be used for illegitimate purposes, e.g. to hide the location of a ship in cases where illegal dumping of waste takes place.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Cloaking however is also used for legitimate reasons such as security concerns, e.g. to protect vessels in transit near the Red Sea from being targeted by terrorist groups.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The containers are currently being repatriated from Singapore to Albania by MSC on their ship *Maria Saveria*.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Since 2024, Maersk has faced criticism and pressure from an international campaign by the Palestinian Youth Movement and its allies to end its role in transporting military cargo and goods to Israel, including to Israeli settlements in the occupied Palestinian territories.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] In November 2024, Maersk container ship *Denver* was denied entry to the Spanish port of Algeciras, due to allegations that the ship was carrying arms supplies to Israel.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 24 February 2025, Maersk's headquarters in Copenhagen was the target of a mass protest action by activists over the transportation of U.S. government military equipment in relation to the Gaza war.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Police cleared the protestors using batons and tear gas after they refused to leave after repeated requests, resulting in the arrest of 22 people.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] Greta Thunberg was among those arrested.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 25 April 2025, dockworkers in Tangier, Morocco refused to load F-35 parts onto a Maersk ship bound for Israel, following days of protests that attracted about 1,500 people.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] On 27 June 2017, Maersk IT systems were the victim of a malware attack utilizing NotPetya, which was designed to appear to be a ransomware attack.
[src:copenhagen/a-p-møller-mærsk] The cyberattack was perpetrated by the Russian military cyberorganization, the GRU, and designed to attack Ukraine, but in fact almost destroyed Maersk Shipping.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The name Aabenraa originally meant "open beach" (Danish: *åben strand*).
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Aabenraa was first mentioned in historic accounts in the 12th century, when it was attacked by the Wends.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Aabenraa started growing in the early Middle Ages around Opnør Hus, the bishop's castle, and received status as a merchant town in 1240, and in 1335 it received a charter.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] During the Middle Ages the town was known for its fishing industry and for its production of hops.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Between 1560 and 1721, the town was under the rule of the Dukes of Holstein-Gottorp.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The town's glory days were during the period of the 1750s to c.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] 1864, when ship traffic was at a high growth rate with trade to the Mediterranean Sea, China, South America, and Australia.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] It possessed a good harbour, which afforded shelter for a large carrying trade, Aabenraa having the Danish monarchy's third-largest trade fleet, after Copenhagen and Flensborg.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The city had a number of shipbuilding yards, which were known for their fine ships.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The best known being the clipper *Cimber*, which in 1857 sailed from Liverpool to San Francisco in 106 days.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Fishing and various small factories also provided occupations for the population.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] From 1864 as a result of the Second War of Schleswig it was part of Prussia, and as such part of the North German Confederation, and from 1871 onwards, part of the German Empire.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] In the 1920 Schleswig Plebiscite that brought Northern Schleswig to Denmark, 55.1% of Aabenraa's inhabitants voted for remaining part of Germany and 44.9% voted for the cession to Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] However, since a plurality of votes in the surrounding Aabenraa municipality voted to join Denmark, the town was thus ceded to the Danish crown.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] After the 1948 Danish spelling reform, which abolished the digraph Aa in favor of Å, there was fervent resistance in Aabenraa.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The town feared, among other things, losing its status as first in alphabetical listings (and reputedly the first town alphabetically anywhere in the world), because the letter *Å* is the last letter in the Dano-Norwegian alphabet.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] A later revision of the spelling rules allowed for retaining the Aa spelling as an option.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] While the municipality of Aabenraa and most local citizens use the Aa spelling, Åbenrå remains the option recommended by the Danish Language Board.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] On June 14, 2019, a low-end IF2/F2/T4 tornado touched down in Aabenraa.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Two vehicles were flipped on the local hospital's parking lot.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Another primarily rated High-end IF1/F1/T3 tornado struck åbenrå on July 13, 2023, causing moderate damage.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Some trees were downed & some buildings were damaged, including one commercial building that had its roof severely blown away.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] 6 cars were damaged with one being moved 50 Centimetres.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The town has a 7.5-meter-deep (25 ft) harbour, with a significant shipping trade.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] There are various industries in the city, including Marcussen's Organ Building (*Marcussens Orgelbyggeri*) and Callesens Machineworks (*Callesens Maskinfabrik*).
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The city is the administrative centre for the county.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Danmarks Radio has an office in the city.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] A German minority lives in Aabenraa, and they publish *Der Nordschleswiger* newspaper in German.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Some noteworthy buildings in the town are St.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Nicholas Church (*Sankt Nicolai Kirke*) from the time of King Valdemar with construction beginning ca.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Brundlund Castle (*Brundlund Slot*), erected by Queen Margaret I in 1411, and rebuilt in 1807, today is home to the Brundlund Slot Art Museum (*Kunstmuseet Brundlund Slot*).
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The town is a bathing resort, as is Elisenlund close by.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The city has several preserved neighborhoods from the 1800s including *Slotsgade*, *Store Pottergade*, *Lille Pottergade*, *Nygade*, *Nybro*, *Skibbrogade* and *Gildegade*.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] A branch of University College South (Danish: *University College Syd*) can be found in Aabenraa.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The Port of Aabenraa is the only remaining active commercial port in Southern Jutland.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] With a depth of 18 metres, it is the deepest port in the eastern part of the Baltic Sea.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] Aabenraa is located close to the European route E45 motorway.
[src:copenhagen/aabenraa] The nearest railway station is Rødekro railway station which is located on the Fredericia–Padborg railway line c.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] Aabybro was a railway town from 1897 until 1969.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] Before the construction of the station, there was a very small settlement in the area.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] The station brought more traffic and expanded the town.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] It was a stop on the Hjørring-Løkken-Aabybro rail line, which operated between 1913 and 1963.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] Aabybro was formerly the seat of Aabybro Municipality.
[src:copenhagen/aabybro] The municipality was established in 1970 and lasted until 2007, when the municipality was merged with the municipalities of Pandrup, Brovst and Fjerritslev to form Jammerbugt Municipality.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Settled as a Viking fishing village in the 10th century in the vicinity of what is now Gammel Strand, Copenhagen became the capital of Denmark in the early 15th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] During the 16th century, the city served as the *de facto* capital of the Kalmar Union and the seat of the Union's monarchy, which governed most of the modern-day Nordic region as part of a Danish confederation with Sweden and Norway.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city flourished as the cultural and economic centre of Scandinavia during the Renaissance.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By the 17th century, it had become a regional centre of power, serving as the heart of the Danish government and military.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] During the 18th century, Copenhagen suffered a devastating plague outbreak and urban conflagrations.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Major redevelopment included the construction of the prestigious district of Frederiksstaden and the establishment of cultural institutions such as the Royal Theatre and the Royal Academy of Fine Arts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city became the centre of the Danish slave trade during this period.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1807, the city was bombarded by a British fleet during the Napoleonic Wars, before the Danish Golden Age brought a Neoclassical look to Copenhagen's architecture.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] After World War II, the Finger Plan fostered the development of housing and businesses along the five urban railway routes emanating from the city centre.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Since the turn of the 21st century, Copenhagen has seen strong urban and cultural development, facilitated by investment in its institutions and infrastructure.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city is the cultural, economic, and governmental centre of Denmark; it is one of the major financial centres of Northern Europe with the Copenhagen Stock Exchange.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen's economy has developed rapidly in the service sector, especially through initiatives in information technology, pharmaceuticals, and clean technology.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Since the completion of the Øresund Bridge, Copenhagen has increasingly integrated with the Swedish province of Scania and its largest city, Malmö, forming the Øresund Region.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] With several bridges connecting the various districts, the cityscape is characterised by parks, promenades, and waterfronts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen's landmarks, such as Tivoli Gardens, *The Little Mermaid* statue, the Amalienborg and Christiansborg palaces, Rosenborg Castle, Frederik's Church, Børsen, and many museums, restaurants, and nightclubs are significant tourist attractions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is home to the University of Copenhagen, the Technical University of Denmark, Copenhagen Business School, and the IT University of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The University of Copenhagen, founded in 1479, is the oldest university in Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is home to the football clubs F.C.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The annual Copenhagen Marathon was established in 1980.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is one of the most bicycle-friendly cities in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Movia is a public mass transit company serving all of eastern Denmark except Bornholm.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen Metro, launched in 2002, serves central Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Additionally, the Copenhagen S-train, the Lokaltog (private railway), and the Coast Line network serve and connect central Copenhagen to outlying boroughs.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Serving roughly 2.7 million passengers a month, Copenhagen Airport, Kastrup, is the busiest airport in the Nordic countries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen's name (*København* in Danish), reflects its origin as a harbour and a place of commerce.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen's Swedish name is *Köpenhamn*, a direct translation of the mutually intelligible Danish name.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city's Latin name *Hafnia*, from the final *havn* or "haven", is the namesake of the element hafnium.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Substantial discoveries of flint tools in the area provide evidence of human settlements dating to the Stone Age.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Many historians believe the town dates to the late Viking Age, and was possibly founded by Sweyn I Forkbeard.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Multiple finds indicate that Copenhagen originated was a city by the 11th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The first habitations were probably centred on Gammel Strand (literally 'old shore') in the 11th century or even earlier.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The natural harbour and good herring stocks seem to have attracted seasonal fishermen and merchants from the 11th century and more permanently in the 13th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Recent archaeological finds during work on the city's rail system revealed the remains of a large merchant mansion from c.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The remains of a church with graves from the 11th century were unearthed near where Strøget meets Rådhuspladsen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Excavations in Pilestræde uncovered a well from the late 12th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The earliest written mention of the town was in the 12th century when Saxo Grammaticus in Gesta Danorum referred to it as *Portus Mercatorum*, meaning "Merchants' Harbour" or, in the Danish of the time, *Købmannahavn*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Traditionally, Copenhagen's founding has been dated to Bishop Absalon's construction of a modest fortress on the little island of Slotsholmen in 1167 where Christiansborg Palace stands today.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] This was in response to attacks by Wendish pirates who plagued the coastline during the 12th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Defensive ramparts and moats were completed, and by 1177 St.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Attacks by the Wends continued, and after the original fortress was eventually destroyed by the marauders, islanders replaced it with Copenhagen Castle.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1186, a letter from Pope Urban III states that King Valdemar I gave the castle of *Hafn* (Copenhagen) and its surrounding lands, including the town of Hafn, to Absalon, Bishop of Roskilde (1158–1191) and Archbishop of Lund (1177–1201).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Upon Absalon's death, the property was to come into the ownership of the Bishopric of Roskilde.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Around 1200, the Church of Our Lady was constructed on higher ground to the northeast of the town, which began to develop around it.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As the town became more prominent, it was repeatedly attacked by the Hanseatic League.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1368, it was successfully invaded during the Second Danish-Hanseatic War.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As the fishing industry thrived in Copenhagen, particularly in the herring trade, the city began expanding to the north of Slotsholmen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1254, it received a city charter under Bishop Jakob Erlandsen who garnered support from the local fishing merchants against the king by granting them special privileges.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the mid 1330s, the first land assessment of the city was published.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] With the establishment of the Kalmar Union (1397–1523) between Denmark, Norway and Sweden, by about 1416 Copenhagen had emerged as the capital of Denmark when Eric of Pomerania moved his seat to Copenhagen Castle.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The University of Copenhagen was inaugurated on 1 June 1479 by King Christian I, following approval from Pope Sixtus IV.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] This makes it the oldest university in Denmark and one of the oldest in Europe.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Originally controlled by the Catholic Church, the university's role in society was forced to change during the Reformation in Denmark in the late 1530s.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Before the Reformation of 1536, the city was faithful to Christian II, who was Catholic.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It was successfully besieged in 1523 by the forces of Frederik I, who supported Lutheranism.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Later, towers were built along the city wall.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city supported Christian II's alliance with Malmö and Lübeck but a siege from July 1535 to July 1536 forced it to capitulate to Christian III.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] During the second half of the century, the city prospered from increased trade across the Baltic supported by Dutch shipping.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Christoffer Valkendorff, a high-ranking statesman, defended the city's interests and contributed to its development.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Netherlands had also become primarily Protestant, as were northern German states.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] During the reign of Christian IV between 1588 and 1648, Copenhagen experienced dramatic growth.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On his initiative, in the early 17th century, two important buildings were completed on Slotsholmen: the Tøjhus Arsenal and Børsen, the stock exchange.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] To foster international trade, the East India Company was founded in 1616.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] East of the city, the king developed the district of Christianshavn with canals and ramparts inspired by Dutch planning.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Intended as a fortified trading centre, it ultimately became part of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Christian IV sponsored many other ambitious building projects including Rosenborg Slot and the Rundetårn.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1658–1659, the city withstood a siege by the Swedes under Charles X and a major assault.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By 1661, Copenhagen had asserted its position as capital of Denmark and Norway.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] All major institutions were located there, as was the fleet and most of the army.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Its defences were enhanced with the completion of the Citadel in 1664 and the extension of Christianshavns Vold with its bastions in 1692, leading to the creation of a new base for the fleet at Nyholm.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen lost some 22,000 of its population of 65,000 to the plague in 1711.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city was also struck by two major fires that destroyed much of its infrastructure.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen Fire of 1728 was the largest in the history of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It began on the evening of 20 October, and burned until the morning of 23 October, destroying 28% of the city as a whole, 47% of the medieval part, and leaving about 20% of the population homeless.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Along with the 1795 fire, it is the main reason why few traces of the old town can be found in the modern city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1733, work began on the royal residence of Christiansborg Palace, completed in 1745.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1749, development of the prestigious district of Frederiksstaden was started.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Designed by Nicolai Eigtved in the Rococo style, its centre contained the mansions which now form Amalienborg Palace.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Major extensions to the naval base of Holmen were undertaken, while the city's cultural importance was enhanced with the Royal Theatre and the Royal Academy of Fine Arts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Danish slave trade began in the 17th century and rapidly expanded in the 18th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Between 1660 and 1806, Danish merchants, many of them based in Copenhagen, transported some 120,000 enslaved Africans to the Danish West Indies.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] These merchants were mostly affiliated with the slave-trading Danish West India Company and Danish Asiatic Company, both of which were headquartered in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Many buildings in Copenhagen, such as the Moltke Mansion, Yellow Palace and the Vestindisk Pakhus were funded with profits from the slave trade.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the second half of the 18th century, Copenhagen benefited from Denmark's neutrality in the wars between Europe's main powers, allowing it to play an important role in trade between the states around the Baltic Sea.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] After the fire of 1794 destroyed Christiansborg and a 1795 fire seriously damaged the city, work began on the classical Copenhagen landmark of Højbro Plads while Nytorv and Gammel Torv were converged.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] To prevent Denmark from allying with France, the British sent Admiral Sir Hyde Parker to attack the Royal Dano-Norwegian Navy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On 2 April 1801, Parker's fleet encountered the Dano-Norwegian navy anchored near Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Vice-Admiral Horatio Nelson led the main attack.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Dano-Norwegian fleet put up heavy resistance, and the battle is often considered Nelson's hardest-fought, surpassing even the battle at Trafalgar.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It was during this battle that Lord Nelson was said to have "put the telescope to the blind eye" in order not to see Admiral Parker's signal to cease fire.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The British ultimately won the battle, sinking or capturing most of the Dano-Norwegian fleet, which led Denmark to agree not to ally with France.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1807, due to continued fears that Denmark would ally with France, Britain sent another fleet, led Admiral James Gambier, to Copenhagen to seize or destroy the Dano-Norwegian navy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The British published a demand to the Dano-Norwegian fleet to surrender.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Danish responded with "what amounted to a declaration of war".
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Then Gambier's fleet bombarded Copenhagen from 2 to 5 September.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The bombardment, which saw the deployment of Congreve rockets, killed 195 civilians and wounded 768, along with burning approximately 1,000 structures, including the Church of Our Lady.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The British artillery had a longer-range than Copenhagen's old defence-line range.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] A British landing force of 30,000 men entered and occupied Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The British suffered almost 200 casualties, while the Danish suffered 3,000.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Virtually the whole Dano-Norwegian fleet surrendered and the British either burnt them or brought them back to Britain.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Denmark declared war on Britain, leading to the Gunboat War, which lasted until the 1814 Treaty of Kiel.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Despite the turmoil the Napoleonic Wars brought to the city, Copenhagen soon experienced a period of intense cultural creativity known as the Danish Golden Age.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Hansen and Gottlieb Bindesbøll brought a Neoclassical look to the city's architecture.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the early 1850s, the ramparts were opened to build housing around The Lakes (Danish: *Søerne*) west of the old defences.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The ramparts were out of date as a defence system, and had limited the city's area, causing poor sanitation.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By the 1880s, the districts of Nørrebro and Vesterbro developed to accommodate those who came from the provinces to participate in the city's industrialization.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] From 1886, the west rampart (Vestvolden) was flattened, allowing major extensions to the harbour leading to the establishment of the Freeport of Copenhagen 1892–94.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Electricity came in 1892 with electric trams in 1897.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The housing outside the old ramparts saw a huge population growth, from 120,000 in 1840 to 400,000 by 1901.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By the beginning of the 20th century, Copenhagen had become a thriving industrial and administrative city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] With its new city hall and railway station, its centre was drawn towards the west.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] New housing developments grew up in Brønshøj and Valby while Frederiksberg became an enclave within the city of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The northern part of Amager and Valby were also incorporated into the City of Copenhagen in 1901–02.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As a result of Denmark's neutrality in the First World War, Copenhagen prospered from trade with both Britain and Germany while the city's defences were kept fully manned by some 40,000 soldiers for the duration of the war.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the 1920s there were serious shortages of goods and housing.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Plans were drawn up to demolish the old part of Christianshavn and to get rid of the worst of the city's slum areas.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] However, it was not until the 1930s that substantial housing developments ensued, with the demolition of one side of Christianhavn's Torvegade to build five large blocks of flats.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In Denmark during World War II, Copenhagen was occupied by German troops along with the rest of the country from 9 April 1940 until 4 May 1945.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] German leader Adolf Hitler hoped that Denmark would be "a model protectorate" and initially the Nazi authorities sought an agreement with the Danish government.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The 1943 Danish parliamentary election was also allowed to take place, with only the Communist Party excluded.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] But in August 1943, after the government's collaboration with the occupation forces collapsed, several ships were sunk in Copenhagen Harbor by the Royal Danish Navy to prevent their use by the Germans.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Around that time the Nazis started to arrest Jews, although most managed to escape to Sweden.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 1945 Ole Lippman, leader of the Danish section of the Special Operations Executive, invited the British Royal Air Force to assist their operations by attacking Nazi headquarters in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Accordingly, air vice-marshal Sir Basil Embry drew up plans for a spectacular precision attack on the Sicherheitsdienst and Gestapo building, the former offices of the Shell Oil Company.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Political prisoners were kept in the attic to prevent an air raid, so the RAF had to bomb the lower levels of the building.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The attack, known as "Operation Carthage", came on 22 March 1945, in three small waves.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the first wave, all six planes (carrying one bomb each) hit their target, but one of the aircraft crashed near Frederiksberg Girls School.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Because of this crash, four of the planes in the two following waves assumed the school was the military target and aimed their bombs at the school, leading to the death of 123 civilians (of which 87 were schoolchildren).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] However, 18 of the 26 political prisoners in the Shell Building managed to escape while the Gestapo archives were completely destroyed.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On 8 May 1945 Copenhagen was officially liberated by British troops commanded by Field Marshal Bernard Montgomery who supervised the surrender of 30,000 Germans situated around the capital.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Soon after the end of the war, an innovative urban development project known as the Finger Plan was introduced in 1947, encouraging the creation of new housing and businesses interspersed with large green areas along five "fingers" stretching out from the city centre along the S-train routes.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] With the expansion of the welfare state and women entering the work force, schools, nurseries, sports facilities and hospitals were established across the city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As a result of student unrest in the late 1960s, the former Bådsmandsstræde Barracks in Christianshavn was occupied, leading to the establishment of Freetown Christiania in September 1971.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Motor traffic in the city grew significantly and in 1972 the trams were replaced by buses.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] From the 1960s, on the initiative of the young architect Jan Gehl, pedestrian streets and cycle tracks were created in the city centre.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Activity in the port of Copenhagen declined with the closure of the Holmen Naval Base.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen Airport underwent considerable expansion, becoming a hub for the Nordic countries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the 1990s, large-scale housing developments were realised in the harbour area and in the west of Amager.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The national library's Black Diamond building on the waterfront was completed in 1999.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Since summer 2000, Copenhagen and the Swedish city of Malmö have been connected by rail and road by the Øresund Bridge.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As a result, Copenhagen has become the centre of a larger metropolitan area spanning both nations.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The bridge has brought about considerable changes in public transport and has led to the extensive redevelopment of Amager.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city's service and trade sectors developed and a number of banking and financial institutions were established.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Educational institutions also gained importance, especially the University of Copenhagen with its 35,000 students.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] An important development for the city was the opening of the Copenhagen Metro railway system in 2002.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] This was extended until 2007, transporting some 54 million passengers by 2011.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen Opera House, a gift to the city from the shipping magnate Mærsk Mc-Kinney Møller on behalf of the A.P.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Møller foundation, was completed in 2004.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In December 2009 Copenhagen hosted the worldwide climate meeting COP15.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 2019 Copenhagen was crowned the *best swimming city* by CNN and Copenhagen harbour now has 13 official swimming zones and three harbour baths.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Illegal bathers are fined by the police.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On 3 July 2022, three people were killed in a shooting at Field's mall in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Police chief inspector Søren Thomassen announced the arrest of a 22-year-old man and said that the police cannot rule out an act of terrorism.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is part of the Øresund Region, which consists of Zealand, Lolland-Falster and Bornholm in Denmark and Scania in Sweden.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It is located on the eastern shore of the island of Zealand, partly on the island of Amager and on a number of natural and artificial islets between the two.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen faces the Øresund to the east, the strait of water that separates Denmark from Sweden, and which connects the North Sea with the Baltic Sea.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Swedish city of Malmö and the town of Landskrona lie on the Swedish side of the sound directly across from Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By road, Copenhagen is 42 kilometres (26 mi) northwest of Malmö, Sweden, 85 kilometres (53 mi) northeast of Næstved, 164 kilometres (102 mi) northeast of Odense, 295 kilometres (183 mi) east of Esbjerg and 188 kilometres (117 mi) southeast of Aarhus by sea and road via Sjællands Odde.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city centre lies in the area originally defined by the old ramparts, which are still referred to as the Fortification Ring (*Fæstningsringen*) and kept as a partial green band around it.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Then come the late-19th- and early-20th-century residential neighbourhoods of Østerbro, Nørrebro, Vesterbro and Amagerbro.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The outlying areas of Kongens Enghave, Valby, Vigerslev, Vanløse, Brønshøj, Utterslev and Sundby followed from 1920 to 1960.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] They consist mainly of residential housing and apartments often enhanced with parks and greenery.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The central area of the city consists of relatively low-lying flat ground formed by moraines from the last ice age while the hilly areas to the north and west frequently rise to 50 m (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The slopes of Valby and Brønshøj reach heights of over 30 m (98 ft), divided by valleys running from the northeast to the southwest.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Close to the centre are the Copenhagen lakes of Sortedams Sø, Peblinge Sø and Sankt Jørgens Sø.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen rests on a subsoil of flint-layered limestone deposited in the Danian period some 60 to 66 million years ago.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Some greensand from the Selandian is also present.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There are a few faults in the area, the most important of which is the Carlsberg fault which runs northwest to southeast through the centre of the city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] During the last ice age, glaciers eroded the surface leaving a layer of moraines up to 15 m (49 ft) thick.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Geologically, Copenhagen lies in the northern part of Denmark where the land is rising because of post-glacial rebound.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Amager Strandpark, which opened in 2005, is a 2 km (1 mi) long artificial island, with a total of 4.6 km (2.9 mi) of beaches.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It is located just 15 minutes by bicycle or a few minutes by metro from the city centre.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In Klampenborg, about 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) from downtown Copenhagen, is Bellevue Beach.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It is 700 metres (2,300 ft) long and has both lifeguards and freshwater showers on the beach.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The beaches are supplemented by a system of Harbour Baths along the Copenhagen waterfront.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The first and most popular of these is located at Islands Brygge, literally meaning Iceland's Quay, and has won international acclaim for its design.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen features a temperate oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*, Trewartha: *Dobk*).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city is located in a climate zone characterized by the influence of the warm Gulf Stream.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] This means that Copenhagen is approximately 5 °C warmer than the city's latitude would otherwise dictate.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Its weather is subject to low-pressure systems from the Atlantic which result in unstable conditions with alternating periods of rain and sun throughout the year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Apart from slightly higher rainfall from July to September, precipitation is moderate.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] While snowfall occurs mainly from late December to early March, there can also be rain, with average temperatures above the freezing point.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] July is the sunniest month of the year with an average of over seven hours of sunshine a day.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] July is the warmest month with an average daytime high of 21 °C.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By contrast, the average hours of sunshine are less than two per day in November and only one and a half per day from December to February.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In the spring, it gets warmer again with four to six hours of sunshine per day from March to May.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] February is the driest month of the year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Exceptional weather conditions can bring as much as 50 cm of snow to Copenhagen in a 24-hour period during the winter months while summer temperatures have been known to rise to heights of 33 °C (91 °F).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Because of Copenhagen's northern latitude, the number of daylight hours varies considerably between summer and winter.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On the summer solstice, the sun rises at 04:26 and sets at 21:58, providing 17 hours 32 minutes of daylight.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] On the winter solstice, it rises at 08:37 and sets at 15:39 with 7 hours and 1 minute of daylight.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There is therefore a difference of 10 hours and 31 minutes in the length of days and nights between the summer and winter solstices.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] They are located in the Capital Region (*Region Hovedstaden*).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Municipalities are responsible for a wide variety of public services, which include land-use planning, environmental planning, public housing, management and maintenance of local roads, and social security.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Municipal administration is also conducted by a mayor, a council, and an executive.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen Municipality is by far the largest municipality, with the historic city at its core.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The seat of Copenhagen's municipal council is the Copenhagen City Hall (**Rådhus**), which is situated on City Hall Square.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The second largest municipality is Frederiksberg, an enclave within Copenhagen Municipality.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen Municipality is divided into ten districts (*bydele*): Indre By, Østerbro, Nørrebro, Vesterbro/Kongens Enghave, Valby, Vanløse, Brønshøj-Husum, Bispebjerg, Amager Øst, and Amager Vest.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Neighbourhoods of Copenhagen include Slotsholmen, Frederiksstaden, Islands Brygge, Holmen, Christiania, Carlsberg, Sluseholmen, Sydhavn, Amagerbro, Ørestad, Nordhavnen, Bellahøj, Brønshøj, Ryparken, and Vigerslev.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Most of Denmark's top legal courts and institutions are based in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] A modern-style court of justice, *Hof- og Stadsretten*, was introduced in Denmark, specifically for Copenhagen, by Johann Friedrich Struensee in 1771.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Now known as the City Court of Copenhagen (*Københavns Byret*), it is the largest of the 24 city courts in Denmark with jurisdiction over the municipalities of Copenhagen, Dragør and Tårnby.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] With its 42 judges, it has a Probate Division, an Enforcement Division and a Registration and Notorial Acts Division while bankruptcy is handled by the Maritime and Commercial Court of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Established in 1862, the Maritime and Commercial Court (*Sø- og Handelsretten*) also hears commercial cases including those relating to trade marks, marketing practices and competition for the whole of Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Denmark's Supreme Court (*Højesteret*), located in Christiansborg Palace on Prins Jørgens Gård in the centre of Copenhagen, is the country's final court of appeal.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Handling civil and criminal cases from the subordinate courts, it has two chambers which each hear all types of cases.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Danish National Police and Copenhagen Police headquarters is situated in the Neoclassical-inspired Politigården building built in 1918–1924 under architects Hack Kampmann and Holger Alfred Jacobsen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The building also contains administration, management, emergency department and radio service offices.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen Fire Department forms the largest municipal fire brigade in Denmark with some 500 fire and ambulance personnel, 150 administration and service workers, and 35 workers in prevention.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The brigade began as the Copenhagen Royal Fire Brigade on 9 July 1687 under King Christian V.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] After the passing of the Copenhagen Fire Act on 18 May 1868, on 1 August 1870 the Copenhagen Fire Brigade became a municipal institution in its own right.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The fire department has its headquarters in the Copenhagen Central Fire Station which was designed by Ludvig Fenger in the Historicist style and inaugurated in 1892.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is recognised as one of the most environmentally friendly cities in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As a result of its commitment to high environmental standards, Copenhagen has been praised for its green economy, ranked as the top green city for the second time in the 2014 *Global Green Economy Index (GGEI)*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 2001 a large offshore wind farm was built just off the coast of Copenhagen at Middelgrunden.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It produces about 4% of the city's energy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Years of substantial investment in sewage treatment have improved water quality in the harbour to an extent that the Inner Harbour can be used for swimming with facilities at a number of locations.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen aims to be carbon-neutral by 2025.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Commercial and residential buildings are to reduce electricity consumption by 20 per cent and 10 per cent respectively, and total heat consumption is to fall by 20 per cent by 2025.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Renewable energy features such as solar panels are becoming increasingly common in the newest buildings in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] District heating will be carbon-neutral by 2025, by waste incineration and biomass.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] New buildings must now be constructed according to Low Energy Class ratings and in 2020 near net-zero energy buildings.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] By 2025, 75% of trips should be made on foot, by bike, or by using public transit.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city plans that 20–30% of cars will run on electricity or biofuel by 2025.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The investment is estimated at $472 million public funds and $4.78 billion private funds.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city's urban planning authorities continue to take full account of these priorities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Special attention is given both to climate issues and efforts to ensure maximum application of low-energy standards.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Priorities include sustainable drainage systems, recycling rainwater, green roofs and efficient waste management solutions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In city planning, streets and squares are to be designed to encourage cycling and walking rather than driving.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is the most populous city in Denmark and one of the most populous in the Nordic countries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] For statistical purposes, Statistics Denmark considers the City of Copenhagen (*Byen København*) to consist of the Municipality of Copenhagen plus three adjacent municipalities: Dragør, Frederiksberg, and Tårnby.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Their combined population stands at 763,908 (as of December 2016).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Municipality of Copenhagen is by far the most populous in the country and one of the most populous Nordic municipalities with 644,431 inhabitants (as of 2022).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There was a demographic boom in the 1990s and first decades of the 21st century, largely due to immigration to Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] According to figures from the first quarter of 2022, 73.7% of the municipality's population was of Danish descent, defined as having at least one parent who was born in Denmark and has Danish citizenship.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Much of the remaining 26.3% were of a foreign background, defined as immigrants (20.3%) or descendants of recent immigrants (6%).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There are no official statistics on ethnic groups.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The adjacent table shows the most common countries of origin of Copenhagen residents.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] According to Statistics Denmark, Copenhagen's urban area has a larger population of 1,280,371 (as of 1 January 2016).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The urban area consists of the municipalities of Copenhagen and Frederiksberg plus 16 of the 20 municipalities of the former counties Copenhagen and Roskilde, though five of them only partially.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Metropolitan Copenhagen has a total of 2,016,285 inhabitants (as of 2016).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The area of Metropolitan Copenhagen is defined by the Finger Plan.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Since the opening of the Øresund Bridge in 2000, commuting between Zealand and Scania in Sweden has increased rapidly, leading to a wider, integrated area.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Known as the Øresund Region, it has 4.1 million inhabitants—of whom 2.7 million (August 2021) live in the Danish part of the region.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In Copenhagen, more than 50% of the households consist of only one adult.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] A majority (56.9%) of those living in Copenhagen are members of the Lutheran Church of Denmark which is 0.6% lower than one year earlier according to 2019 figures.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The National Cathedral, the Church of Our Lady, is one of the dozens of churches in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There are also several other Christian communities in the city, of which the largest is Roman Catholic.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Foreign migration to Copenhagen, rising over the last three decades, has contributed to increasing religious diversity; the Grand Mosque of Copenhagen, the first in Denmark, opened in 2014.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Islam is the second largest religion in Copenhagen, accounting for approximately 10% of the population.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] While there are no official statistics, a significant portion of the estimated 175,000–200,000 Muslims in the country live in the Copenhagen urban area, with the highest concentration in Nørrebro and the Vestegnen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There are also some 7,000 Jews in Denmark, most of them in the Copenhagen area where there are several synagogues.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] There is a long history of Jews in the city, and the first synagogue in Copenhagen was built in 1684.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Today, the history of the Jews of Denmark can be explored at the Danish Jewish Museum in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] For a number of years, Copenhagen has ranked high in international surveys for its quality of life.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Its stable economy together with its education services and level of social safety make it attractive for locals and visitors alike.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Although it is one of the world's most expensive cities, it is also one of the most liveable with its public transport, facilities for cyclists and its environmental policies.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In elevating Copenhagen to "most liveable city" in 2013, *Monocle* pointed to its open spaces, increasing activity on the streets, city planning in favour of cyclists and pedestrians, and features to encourage inhabitants to enjoy city life with an emphasis on community, culture and cuisine.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city was voted 2024 second most liveable city by Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Other sources have ranked Copenhagen high for its business environment, accessibility, restaurants and environmental planning.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] However, Copenhagen ranks only 39th for student friendliness in 2012.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Despite a top score for quality of living, its scores were low for employer activity and affordability.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is the major economic and financial centre of Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city's economy is based largely on services and commerce.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Statistics for 2010 show that the vast majority of the 350,000 workers in Copenhagen are employed in the service sector, especially transport and communications, trade, and finance, while less than 10,000 work in the manufacturing industries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The public sector workforce is around 110,000, including education and healthcare.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] From 2006 to 2011, the economy grew by 2.5% in Copenhagen, while it fell by some 4% in the rest of Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 2017, the wider Capital Region of Denmark had a gross domestic product (GDP) of €120 billion, and the 15th largest GDP per capita of regions in the European Union.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] As of Copenhagen Green Economy Leader Report made by London School of Economics and Political Science – Copenhagen is widely recognised as a leader in the global green economy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen region accounts for almost 40% of Denmark's output and has enjoyed long-term stable growth.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] At a national level, Danish GDP per capita is ranked among the top 10 countries in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] At the same time, the city's growth has been delivered while improving environmental performance and transitioning to a low-carbon economy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Several financial institutions and banks have headquarters in Copenhagen, including Alm.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Brand, Danske Bank, Nykredit and Nordea Bank Danmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The Copenhagen Stock Exchange (CSE) was founded in 1620 and is now owned by Nasdaq, Inc.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is also home to a number of international companies including A.P.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Møller-Mærsk, Novo Nordisk, Carlsberg and Novozymes.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] City authorities have encouraged the development of business clusters in several innovative sectors, which include information technology, biotechnology, pharmaceuticals, clean technology and smart city solutions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Life science is a key sector with extensive research and development activities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Medicon Valley is a leading bi-national life sciences cluster in Europe, spanning the Øresund Region.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen is rich in companies and institutions with a focus on research and development within the field of biotechnology, and the Medicon Valley initiative aims to strengthen this position and to promote cooperation between companies and academia.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Many major Danish companies like Novo Nordisk and Lundbeck, both of which are among the 50 largest pharmaceutical and biotech companies in the world, are located in this business cluster.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Shipping is another important sector with Maersk, the world's largest shipping company, having their world headquarters in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The city has an industrial harbour, Copenhagen Port.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Following decades of stagnation, it has experienced a resurgence since 1990 following a merger with Malmö harbour.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Both ports are operated by Copenhagen Malmö Port (CMP).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The central location in the Øresund Region allows the ports to act as a hub for freight that is transported onward to the Baltic countries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] CMP annually receives about 8,000 ships and handled some 148,000 TEU in 2012.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Copenhagen has some of the highest gross wages in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] High taxes mean that wages are reduced after mandatory deduction.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] A *beneficial researcher scheme* with low taxation of foreign specialists has made Denmark an attractive location for foreign labour.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] It is, however, also among the most expensive cities in Europe.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Denmark's Flexicurity model features some of the most flexible hiring and firing legislation in Europe, providing attractive conditions for foreign investment and international companies looking to locate in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The survey revealed considerable dissatisfaction in the level of dialogue companies enjoyed with the municipal authorities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Tourism is a major contributor to Copenhagen's economy, attracting visitors due to the city's harbour, cultural attractions and award-winning restaurants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Since 2009, Copenhagen has been one of the fastest growing metropolitan destinations in Europe.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] Hotel capacity in the city is growing significantly.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] From 2009 to 2013, it experienced a 42% growth in international bed nights (total number of nights spent by tourists), tallying a rise of nearly 70% for Chinese visitors.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] The total number of bed nights in the Capital Region surpassed 9 million in 2013, while international bed nights reached 5 million.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 2010, it is estimated that city break tourism contributed to DKK 2 billion in turnover.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] However, 2010 was an exceptional year for city break tourism and turnover increased with 29% in that one year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] 680,000 cruise passengers visited the port in 2015.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In 2019 Copenhagen was ranked first among Lonely Planet's top ten cities to visit.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p01] In October 2021, Copenhagen was shortlisted for the European Commission's 2022 European Capital of Smart Tourism award along with Bordeaux, Dublin, Florence, Ljubljana, Palma de Mallorca and Valencia.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city skyline features many towers and spires.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city's appearance today is shaped by the key role it has played as a regional centre for centuries.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has a multitude of districts, each with its distinctive character and representing its own period.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other distinctive features of Copenhagen include the abundance of water, its many parks, and the bicycle paths that line most streets.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] is a 17th-century waterfront lined by brightly coloured townhouses.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The oldest section of Copenhagen's inner city is often referred to as *Middelalderbyen* (the medieval city).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] However, the city's most distinctive district is Frederiksstaden, developed during the reign of Frederick V.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It has the Amalienborg Palace at its centre and is dominated by the dome of Frederik's Church (or the Marble Church) and several elegant 18th-century Rococo mansions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The inner city includes Slotsholmen, a little island on which Christiansborg Palace stands and Christianshavn with its canals.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Børsen on Slotsholmen and Frederiksborg Palace in Hillerød are prominent examples of the Dutch Renaissance style in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Around the historical city centre lies a band of congenial residential boroughs (Vesterbro, Inner Nørrebro, Inner Østerbro) dating mainly from late 19th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] They were built outside the old ramparts when the city was finally allowed to expand beyond its fortifications.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Sometimes referred to as "the City of Spires", Copenhagen is known for its generally horizontal skyline, broken mainly by the spires and towers of its churches and castles.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Most characteristic of all is the Baroque spire of the Church of Our Saviour with its narrowing external spiral stairway that visitors can climb to the top.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other important spires are those of Christiansborg Palace, the City Hall and the former Church of St.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Nikolaj that now houses a modern art venue.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Not quite so high are the Renaissance spires of Rosenborg Castle and the "dragon spire" of Christian IV's former stock exchange, so named because it resembles the intertwined tails of four dragons.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen is recognised globally as an exemplar of best practice urban planning.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Its thriving mixed use city centre is defined by striking contemporary architecture, engaging public spaces and an abundance of human activity.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] These design outcomes have been deliberately achieved through careful replanning in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Recent years have seen a boom in modern architecture in Copenhagen both for Danish architecture and for works by international architects.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] For a few hundred years, virtually no foreign architects had worked in Copenhagen, but since the turn of the millennium the city and its immediate surroundings have seen buildings and projects designed by top international architects.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] British design magazine *Monocle* named Copenhagen the *World's best design city 2008*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen's urban development in the first half of the 20th century was heavily influenced by industrialisation.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] After World War II, Copenhagen Municipality adopted Fordism and repurposed its medieval centre to facilitate private automobile infrastructure in response to innovations in transport, trade and communication.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen's spatial planning in this time frame was characterised by the separation of land uses: an approach which requires residents to travel by car to access facilities of different uses.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The boom in urban development and modern architecture has brought some changes to the city's skyline.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] A political majority has decided to keep the historical centre free of high-rise buildings, but several areas will see or have already seen massive urban development. Ørestad now has seen most of the recent development.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Located near Copenhagen Airport, it currently boasts one of the largest malls in Scandinavia and a variety of office and residential buildings as well as the IT University and a high school.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen is a green city with many parks, both large and small.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] King's Garden (**Kongens Have**), the garden of Rosenborg Castle, is the oldest and most frequented of them all.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It was Christian IV who first developed its landscaping in 1606.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Every year it sees more than 2.5 million visitors and in the summer months it is packed with sunbathers, picnickers and ballplayers.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It serves as a sculpture garden with both a permanent display and temporary exhibits during the summer months.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Also located in the city centre are the Botanical Gardens noted for their large complex of 19th-century greenhouses donated by Carlsberg founder J.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Fælledparken at 58 ha (140 acres) is the largest park in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is popular for sports fixtures and hosts several annual events including a free opera concert at the opening of the opera season, other open-air concerts, carnival and Labour Day celebrations, and the Copenhagen Historic Grand Prix, a race for antique cars.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] A historical green space in the northeastern part of the city is Kastellet, a well-preserved Renaissance citadel that now serves mainly as a park.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Another popular park is the Frederiksberg Gardens, a 32-hectare romantic landscape park.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It houses a colony of tame grey herons and other waterfowl.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The park offers views of the elephant house of the adjacent Copenhagen Zoo, designed by world-famous British architect Norman Foster.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Langelinie, a park and promenade along the inner Øresund coast, is home to one of Copenhagen's most-visited tourist attractions, the Little Mermaid statue.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In Copenhagen, many cemeteries double as parks, though only for the more quiet activities such as sunbathing, reading and meditation.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Assistens Cemetery, the burial place of Hans Christian Andersen, is an important green space for the district of Inner Nørrebro and a Copenhagen institution.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The lesser known Vestre Kirkegaard is the largest cemetery in Denmark (54 ha (130 acres)) and offers a maze of dense groves, open lawns, winding paths, hedges, overgrown tombs, monuments, tree-lined avenues, lakes and other garden features.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is official municipal policy in Copenhagen that by 2015 all citizens must be able to reach a park or beach on foot in less than 15 minutes.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In line with this policy, several new parks, including the innovative Superkilen in the Nørrebro district, have been completed or are under development in areas lacking green spaces.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The historic centre of the city, Indre By or the Inner City, features many of Copenhagen's most popular monuments and attractions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The area known as Frederiksstaden, developed by Frederik V in the second half of the 18th century in the Rococo style, has the four mansions of Amalienborg, the royal residence, and the wide-domed Marble Church at its centre.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Directly across the water from Amalienborg, the 21st-century Copenhagen Opera House stands on the island of Holmen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] To the south of Frederiksstaden, the Nyhavn canal is lined with colourful houses from the 17th and 18th centuries, many now with lively restaurants and bars.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The canal runs from the harbour front to the spacious square of Kongens Nytorv which was laid out by Christian V in 1670.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Important buildings include Charlottenborg Palace, famous for its art exhibitions, the Thott Palace (now the French embassy), the Royal Danish Theatre and the Hotel D'Angleterre, dated to 1755.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other landmarks in Indre By include the parliament building of Christiansborg, the City Hall and Rundetårn, originally an observatory.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] There are also several museums in the area including Thorvaldsen Museum dedicated to the 18th-century sculptor Bertel Thorvaldsen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Closed to traffic since 1964, Strøget, one of the world's oldest and longest pedestrian streets, runs the 3.2 km (2.0 mi) from Rådhuspladsen to Kongens Nytorv.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] With its speciality shops, cafés, restaurants, and buskers, it is always full of life and includes the old squares of Gammel Torv and Amagertorv, each with a fountain.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Rosenborg Castle on Øster Voldgade was built by Christian IV in 1606 as a summer residence in the Renaissance style.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It houses the Danish crown jewels and crown regalia, the coronation throne and tapestries illustrating Christian V's victories in the Scanian War.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Christianshavn lies to the southeast of Indre By on the other side of the harbour.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The area was developed by Christian IV in the early 17th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Impressed by the city of Amsterdam, he employed Dutch architects to create canals within its ramparts which are still well preserved today.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The canals themselves, branching off the central Christianshavn Canal and lined with house boats and pleasure craft are one of the area's attractions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Another interesting feature is Freetown Christiania, a fairly large area which was initially occupied by squatters during student unrest in 1971.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Today it still maintains a measure of autonomy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The inhabitants openly sell drugs on "Pusher Street" as well as their arts and crafts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other buildings of interest in Christianshavn include the Church of Our Saviour with its spiralling steeple and the magnificent Rococo Christian's Church.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Once a warehouse, the North Atlantic House now displays culture from Iceland and Greenland and houses the Noma restaurant, known for its Nordic cuisine.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Vesterbro, to the southwest of Indre By, begins with the Tivoli Gardens, the city's top tourist attraction with its fairground atmosphere, its Pantomime Theatre, its Concert Hall and its many rides and restaurants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Carlsberg neighbourhood has some interesting vestiges of the old brewery of the same name including the Elephant Gate and the Ny Carlsberg Brewhouse.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Tycho Brahe Planetarium is located on the edge of Skt.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Jørgens Sø, one of the Copenhagen lakes.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Halmtorvet, the old hay market behind the Central Station, is an increasingly popular area with its cafés and restaurants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The former cattle market Øksnehallen has been converted into a modern exhibition centre for art and photography.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Radisson Blu Royal Hotel, built by Danish architect and designer Arne Jacobsen for the airline Scandinavian Airlines System (SAS) between 1956 and 1960 was once the tallest hotel in Denmark with a height of 69.60 m (228.3 ft) and the city's only skyscraper until 1969.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Completed in 1908, Det Ny Teater (the New Theatre) located in a passage between Vesterbrogade and Gammel Kongevej has become a popular venue for musicals since its reopening in 1994, attracting the largest audiences in the country.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Nørrebro to the northwest of the city centre has recently developed from a working-class district into a colourful cosmopolitan area with antique shops, non-Danish food stores and restaurants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Much of the activity is centred on Sankt Hans Torv and around Rantzausgade.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen's historic cemetery, Assistens Kirkegård halfway up Nørrebrogade, is the resting place of many famous figures including Søren Kierkegaard, Niels Bohr, and Hans Christian Andersen but is also used by locals as a park and recreation area.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Just north of the city centre, Østerbro is an upper middle-class district with a number of fine mansions, some now serving as embassies.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The district stretches from Nørrebro to the waterfront where *The Little Mermaid* statue can be seen from the promenade known as Langelinie.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Inspired by Hans Christian Andersen's fairy tale, it was created by Edvard Eriksen and unveiled in 1913.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Not far from the Little Mermaid, the old Citadel (*Kastellet*) can be seen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Built by Christian IV, it is one of northern Europe's best preserved fortifications.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The large Gefion Fountain (*Gefionspringvandet*) designed by Anders Bundgaard and completed in 1908 stands close to the southeast corner of Kastellet.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Frederiksberg, a separate municipality within the urban area of Copenhagen, lies to the west of Nørrebro and Indre By and north of Vesterbro.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Its landmarks include Copenhagen Zoo founded in 1869 with over 250 species from all over the world and Frederiksberg Palace built as a summer residence by Frederick IV who was inspired by Italian architecture.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Now a military academy, it overlooks the extensive landscaped Frederiksberg Gardens with its follies, waterfalls, lakes and decorative buildings.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The wide tree-lined avenue of Frederiksberg Allé connecting Vesterbrogade with the Frederiksberg Gardens has long been associated with theatres and entertainment.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] While a number of the earlier theatres are now closed, the Betty Nansen Theatre and Aveny-T are still active.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Amagerbro (also known as Sønderbro) is the district located immediately south-east of Christianshavn at northernmost Amager.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The old city moats and their surrounding parks constitute a clear border between these districts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The main street is Amagerbrogade which after the harbour bridge Langebro, is an extension of H.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Andersens Boulevard and has a number of various stores and shops as well as restaurants and pubs.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Amagerbro was built up during the two first decades of the twentieth century and is the city's southernmost block built area with typically 4–7 floors.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Further south follows the Sundbyøster and Sundbyvester districts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Not far from Copenhagen Airport on the Kastrup coast, The Blue Planet completed in March 2013 now houses the national aquarium.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] With its 53 aquariums, it is the largest facility of its kind in Scandinavia.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Grundtvig's Church, located in the northern suburb of Bispebjerg, was designed by P.V.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] A rare example of Expressionist church architecture, its striking west façade is reminiscent of a church organ.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Apart from being the national capital, Copenhagen also serves as the cultural hub of Denmark and one of the major hubs in wider Scandinavia.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Since the late 1990s, it has undergone a transformation from a modest Scandinavian capital into a metropolitan city of international appeal, in the same league as cities such as Barcelona and Amsterdam.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] This is a result of huge investments in infrastructure and culture as well as the work of successful new Danish architects, designers and chefs.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Fashion Week takes place every year in February and August.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has a wide array of museums of international standing.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The National Museum, *Nationalmuseet*, is Denmark's largest museum of archaeology and cultural history, comprising the histories of Danish and foreign cultures alike.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Denmark's National Gallery (*Statens Museum for Kunst*) is the national art museum with collections dating from the 12th century to the present.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In addition to Danish painters, artists represented in the collections include Rubens, Rembrandt, Picasso, Braque, Léger, Matisse, Emil Nolde, Olafur Eliasson, Elmgreen & Dragset, Superflex, and Jens Haaning.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Another important Copenhagen art museum is the Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek founded by second generation Carlsberg philanthropist Carl Jacobsen and built around his personal collections.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Its main focus is classical Egyptian, Roman and Greek sculptures and antiquities and a collection of Rodin sculptures, the largest outside France.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Besides its sculpture collections, the museum also holds a comprehensive collection of paintings of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist painters such as Monet, Renoir, Cézanne, van Gogh and Toulouse-Lautrec as well as works by the Danish Golden Age painters.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Louisiana is a Museum of Modern Art situated on the coast just north of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is located in the middle of a sculpture garden on a cliff overlooking Øresund.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Its collection of over 3,000 items includes works by Picasso, Giacometti and Dubuffet.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Danish Design Museum is housed in the 18th-century former Frederiks Hospital and displays Danish design as well as international design and crafts.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Royal Danish Theatre stages opera and drama productions, and is also home to the Royal Danish Ballet.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Founded in 1748 along with the theatre, it is one of the oldest ballet troupes in Europe, and is noted for its Bournonville style of ballet.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Royal Danish Playhouse is a new building, completed in 2008, that is part of the Royal Danish Theatre.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The new Copenhagen Concert Hall opened in January 2009.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Designed by Jean Nouvel, it has four halls with the main auditorium seating 1,800 people.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It serves as the home of the Danish National Symphony Orchestra and, along with the Walt Disney Concert Hall in Los Angeles, is one of the most expensive concert halls ever built.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Another important venue for classical music is the Tivoli Concert Hall located in the Tivoli Gardens.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Danish National School of Performing Arts (DASPA) has a campus in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Before being amalgamated with five other schools in 2015, it was known as the Statens Scenekunstskole, or National Performing Arts School.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Designed by Henning Larsen, the Copenhagen Opera House (*Operaen*) opened in 2005.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is among the most modern opera houses in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has a significant jazz scene that has existed for many years.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It developed when a number of American jazz musicians such as Ben Webster, Thad Jones, Richard Boone, Ernie Wilkins, Kenny Drew, Ed Thigpen, Bob Rockwell, Dexter Gordon, and others such as rock guitarist Link Wray came to live in Copenhagen during the 1960s.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Every year in early July, Copenhagen's streets, squares, parks as well as cafés and concert halls fill up with big and small jazz concerts during the Copenhagen Jazz Festival.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] One of Europe's top jazz festivals, the annual event features around 900 concerts at 100 venues with over 200,000 guests from Denmark and around the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The largest venue for popular music in Copenhagen is Vega in the Vesterbro district.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It was chosen as "best concert venue in Europe" by international music magazine *Live*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The venue has three concert halls: the great hall, Store Vega, accommodates audiences of 1,550, the middle hall, Lille Vega, has space for 500 and Ideal Bar Live has a capacity of 250.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Every September since 2006, the Festival of Endless Gratitude (FOEG) has taken place in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] This festival focuses on indie counterculture, experimental pop music and left field music combined with visual arts exhibitions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] For free entertainment one can stroll along Strøget, especially between Nytorv and Højbro Plads, which in the late afternoon and evening is a bit like an impromptu three-ring circus with musicians, magicians, jugglers and other street performers.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Most of Denmarks's major publishing houses are based in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] These include the book publishers Gyldendal and Akademisk Forlag and newspaper publishers Berlingske and Politiken (the latter also publishing books).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Many of the most important contributors to Danish literature such as Hans Christian Andersen (1805–1875) with his fairy tales, the philosopher Søren Kierkegaard (1813–1855) and playwright Ludvig Holberg (1684–1754) spent much of their lives in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Michael Frayn's 1998 play *Copenhagen* about the meeting between the physicists Niels Bohr and Werner Heisenberg in 1941 is also set in the city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Tove Ditlevsen wrote a series of memoirs, called *The Copenhagen Trilogy*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] On 15–18 August 1973, an oral literature conference took place in Copenhagen as part of the 9th International Congress of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Royal Library, belonging to the University of Copenhagen, is the largest library in the Nordic countries with an almost complete collection of all printed Danish books since 1482.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Founded in 1648, the Royal Library is located at four sites in the city, the main one being on the Slotsholmen waterfront.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen's public library network has over 20 outlets, the largest being the Central Library (*Københavns Hovedbibliotek*) on Krystalgade in the inner city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has a wide selection of art museums and galleries displaying both historic works and more modern contributions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] They include Statens Museum for Kunst, i.e. the Danish national art gallery, in the Østre Anlæg park, and the adjacent Hirschsprung Collection specialising in the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Kunsthal Charlottenborg in the city centre exhibits national and international contemporary art.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Den Frie Udstilling near the Østerport Station exhibits paintings created and selected by contemporary artists themselves rather than by the official authorities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Arken Museum of Modern Art is located in southwestern Ishøj.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Among artists who have painted scenes of Copenhagen are Martinus Rørbye (1803–1848), Christen Købke (1810–1848) and the prolific Paul Gustav Fischer (1860–1934).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] A number of notable sculptures can be seen in the city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Rosenborg Castle Gardens contains several sculptures and monuments including August Saabye's Hans Christian Andersen, Aksel Hansen's Echo, and Vilhelm Bissen's Dowager Queen Caroline Amalie.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen is believed to have invented the photomarathon photography competition, which has been held in the City each year since 1989.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] As of 2014, Copenhagen has 15 Michelin-starred restaurants, the most of any Scandinavian city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city is increasingly recognized internationally as a gourmet destination.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Noma was ranked as the Best Restaurant in the World by *Restaurant* in 2010, 2011, 2012, and again in 2014, sparking interest in the New Nordic Cuisine.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Apart from the selection of upmarket restaurants, Copenhagen offers a great variety of Danish, ethnic and experimental restaurants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is possible to find modest eateries serving open sandwiches, known as smørrebrød – a traditional, Danish lunch dish; however, most restaurants serve international dishes.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Danish pastry can be sampled from any of numerous bakeries found in all parts of the city.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Copenhagen Bakers' Association (Danish: *Københavns Bagerlaug*) dates back to the 1290s and Denmark's oldest confectioner's shop still operating, *Conditori La Glace*, was founded in 1870 in Skoubogade by Nicolaus Henningsen, a trained master baker from Flensburg.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has long been associated with beer.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Carlsberg beer has been brewed at the brewery's premises on the border between the Vesterbro and Valby districts since 1847 and has long been almost synonymous with Danish beer production.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] However, recent years have seen an explosive growth in the number of microbreweries so that Denmark today has more than 100 breweries, many of which are located in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Some like Nørrebro Bryghus also act as brewpubs where it is also possible to eat on the premises.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has one of the highest number of restaurants and bars per capita in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The nightclubs and bars stay open until 5 or 6 in the morning, some even longer.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Denmark has a very liberal alcohol culture and a strong tradition for beer breweries, although binge drinking is frowned upon and the Danish Police take driving under the influence very seriously.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Inner city areas such as Istedgade and Enghave Plads in Vesterbro, Sankt Hans Torv in Nørrebro and certain places in Frederiksberg are especially noted for their nightlife.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Notable nightclubs include Bakken Kbh, ARCH (previously ZEN), Jolene, The Jane, Chateau Motel, KB3, At Dolores (previously Sunday Club), Rust, Vega Nightclub and Culture Box.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has several recurring community festivals, mainly in the summer.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Carnival has taken place every year since 1982 during the Whitsun Holiday in Fælledparken and around the city with the participation of 120 bands, 2,000 dancers and 100,000 spectators.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Since 2010, the old B&W Shipyard at Refshaleøen in the harbour has been the location for Copenhell, a heavy metal rock music festival.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Pride is a LGBT pride festival taking place every year in August.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Pride has a series of different activities all over Copenhagen, but it is at the City Hall Square that most of the celebration takes place.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] During the Pride the square is renamed Pride Square.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Distortion has emerged to be one of the biggest street festivals in Europe with 100,000 people joining to parties in the beginning of June every year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has the oldest and third-oldest amusement parks in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Dyrehavsbakken, a fair-ground and pleasure-park established in 1583, is located in Klampenborg just north of Copenhagen in a forested area known as Dyrehaven.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Created as an amusement park complete with rides, games and restaurants by Christian IV, it is the oldest surviving amusement park in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Pierrot (Danish: *Pjerrot*), a nitwit dressed in white with a scarlet grin wearing a boat-like hat while entertaining children, remains one of the park's key attractions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In Danish, Dyrehavsbakken is often abbreviated as *Bakken*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] There is no entrance fee to pay and Klampenborg Station on the C-line, is situated nearby.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Tivoli Gardens is an amusement park and pleasure garden located in central Copenhagen between the City Hall Square and the Central Station.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It opened in 1843, making it the third-oldest amusement park in the world, the second being Wurstelprater in Vienna.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Among its rides are the oldest still operating rollercoaster *Rutschebanen* from 1915 and the oldest ferris wheel still in use, opened in 1943.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Tivoli Gardens also serves as a venue for various performing arts and as an active part of the cultural scene in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] 4,500 students), IT University of Copenhagen (2,000 students) and the Copenhagen campus of Aalborg University (2,300 students).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The University of Copenhagen is Denmark's oldest university founded in 1479.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It attracts some 1,500 international and exchange students every year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Academic Ranking of World Universities placed it 30th in the world in 2016.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Technical University of Denmark is located in Lyngby in the northern outskirts of Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In 2013, it was ranked as one of the leading technical universities in Northern Europe.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The IT University is Denmark's youngest university, a mono-faculty institution focusing on technical, societal and business aspects of information technology.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Danish Academy of Fine Arts has provided education in the arts for more than 250 years.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It includes the historic School of Visual Arts, and has in later years come to include a School of Architecture, a School of Design and a School of Conservation.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Business School (CBS) is an EQUIS-accredited business school located in Frederiksberg.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] There are also branches of both University College Capital and Metropolitan University College inside and outside Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city has a variety of sporting teams.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The major football teams are the historically successful FC København and Brøndby.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] FC København plays at Parken in Østerbro.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Formed in 1992, it is a merger of two older Copenhagen clubs, B 1903 (from the inner suburb Gentofte) and KB (from Frederiksberg).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Brøndby plays at Brøndby Stadion in the inner suburb of Brøndbyvester.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] BK Frem is based in the southern part of Copenhagen (Sydhavnen, Valby).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other teams of more significant stature are FC Nordsjælland (from suburban Farum), Fremad Amager, B93, AB, Lyngby and Hvidovre IF.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has several handball teams—a sport which is particularly popular in Denmark.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Clubs playing in the "highest" leagues include Ajax, Ydun, and HIK (Hellerup).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The København Håndbold women's club has recently been established.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen also has ice hockey teams, of which three play in the top league, Rødovre Mighty Bulls, Herlev Eagles and Hvidovre Ligahockey all inner suburban clubs.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Ice Skating Club founded in 1869 is the oldest ice hockey team in Denmark but is no longer in the top league.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Rugby union is also played in the Danish capital with teams such as CSR-Nanok, Copenhagen Business School Sport Rugby, Frederiksberg RK, Exiles RUFC and Rugbyklubben Speed.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Rugby league is now played in Copenhagen, with the national team playing out of Gentofte Stadion.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Danish Australian Football League, based in Copenhagen is the largest Australian rules football competition outside of the English-speaking world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Marathon, Copenhagen's annual marathon event, was established in 1980.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Round Christiansborg Open Water Swim Race is a 2-kilometre (1.2-mile) open water swimming competition taking place each year in late August.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] This amateur event is combined with a 10-kilometre (6-mile) Danish championship.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In 2009 the event included a 10-kilometre (6-mile) FINA World Cup competition in the morning.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen hosted the 2011 UCI Road World Championships in September 2011, taking advantage of its bicycle-friendly infrastructure.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It was the first time that Denmark had hosted the event since 1956, when it was also held in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The greater Copenhagen area has a very well established transportation infrastructure making it a hub in Northern Europe.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Airport, opened in 1925, is Scandinavia's largest airport, located in Kastrup on the island of Amager.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It is connected to the city centre by metro and main line railway services.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] October 2013 was a record month with 2.2 million passengers, and November 2013 figures reveal that the number of passengers is increasing by some 3% annually, about 50% more than the European average.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has an extensive road network including motorways connecting the city to other parts of Denmark and to Sweden over the Øresund Bridge.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The car is still the most popular form of transport within the city itself, representing two-thirds of all distances travelled.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] This can however lead to serious congestion in rush hour traffic.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Øresund train links Copenhagen with Malmö 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen is also served by a daily ferry connection to Oslo in Norway.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In 2012, Copenhagen Harbour handled 372 cruise ships and 840,000 passengers.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Copenhagen S-Train, Copenhagen Metro and the regional train networks are used by about half of the city's passengers, the remainder using bus services.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Nørreport Station near the city centre serves passengers travelling by main-line rail, S-train, regional train, metro and bus.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Some 750,000 passengers make use of public transport facilities every day.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen Central Station is the hub of the DSB railway network serving Denmark and international destinations.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The Copenhagen Metro expanded radically with the opening of the City Circle Line (M3) on 29 September 2019.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The new line connects all inner boroughs of the city by metro, including the Central Station, and opens up 17 new stations for Copenhageners.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] On 28 March 2020, the 2.2 km (1.4 mi) Nordhavn extension of the Harbour Line (M4) opened.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Running from Copenhagen Central Station, the new extension is a branch line of M3 Cityring to Østerport.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The new metro lines are part of the city's strategy to transform mobility towards sustainable modes of transport such as public transport and cycling as opposed to automobility.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen is cited by urban planners for its exemplary integration of public transport and urban development.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In implementing its Finger Plan, Copenhagen is considered the world's first example of a transit metropolis, and areas around S-Train stations like Ballerup and Brøndby Strand are among the earliest examples of transit-oriented development.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has been rated as one of the most bicycle-friendly cities in the world since 2015, with bicycles outnumbering its inhabitants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In 2012 some 36% of all working or studying city-dwellers cycled to work, school, or university.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] With 1.27 million km (790,000 mi) covered every working day by Copenhagen's cyclists (including both residents and commuters), and 75% of Copenhageners cycling throughout the year.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city's bicycle paths are extensive and well used, boasting 400 kilometres (250 miles) of cycle lanes not shared with cars or pedestrians, and sometimes equipped with their own signal systems – giving the cyclists a lead of a couple of seconds to accelerate.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Promoting health is an important issue for Copenhagen's municipal authorities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Central to its sustainability mission is its "Long Live Copenhagen" (*Længe Leve København*) scheme in which it has the goal of increasing the life expectancy of citizens, improving quality of life through better standards of health, and encouraging more productive lives and equal opportunities.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The city has targets to encourage people to exercise regularly and to reduce the number of people who smoke and consume alcohol.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen University Hospital forms a conglomerate of several hospitals in Region Hovedstaden and Region Sjælland, together with the faculty of health sciences at the University of Copenhagen; Rigshospitalet and Bispebjerg Hospital in Copenhagen belong to this group of university hospitals.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Rigshospitalet began operating in March 1757 as Frederiks Hospital, and became state-owned in 1903.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] With 1,120 beds, Rigshospitalet has responsibility for 65,000 inpatients and approximately 420,000 outpatients annually.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It seeks to be the number one specialist hospital in the country, with an extensive team of researchers into cancer treatment, surgery and radiotherapy.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In addition to its 8,000 personnel, the hospital has training and hosting functions.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] It benefits from the presence of in-service students of medicine and other healthcare sciences, as well as scientists working under a variety of research grants.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The hospital became internationally famous as the location of Lars von Trier's television horror mini-series *The Kingdom*.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Bispebjerg Hospital was built in 1913, and serves about 400,000 people in the Greater Copenhagen area, with some 3,000 employees.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other large hospitals in the city include Amager Hospital (1997), Herlev Hospital (1976), Hvidovre Hospital (1970), and Gentofte Hospital (1927).
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Many Danish media corporations are located in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] DR, the major Danish public service broadcasting corporation consolidated its activities in a new headquarters, DR Byen, in 2006 and 2007.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Similarly TV2, which is based in Odense, has concentrated its Copenhagen activities in a modern media house in Teglholmen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The two national daily newspapers *Politiken* and *Berlingske* and the two tabloids *Ekstra Bladet* and *BT* are based in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] *Kristeligt Dagblad* is based in Copenhagen and is published six days a week.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Other important media corporations include Aller Media which is the largest publisher of weekly and monthly magazines in Scandinavia, the Egmont media group and Gyldendal, the largest Danish publisher of books.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Copenhagen has a large film and television industry.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Nordisk Film, established in Valby, Copenhagen in 1906 is the oldest continuously operating film production company in the world.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In 1992 it merged with the Egmont media group and currently runs the 17-screen Palads Cinema in Copenhagen.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Filmbyen (movie city), located in a former military camp in the suburb of Hvidovre, houses several movie companies and studios.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] Zentropa is a film company, co-owned by Danish director Lars von Trier.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] He is behind several international movie productions as well and founded the Dogme Movement.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] CPH:PIX is Copenhagen's international feature film festival, established in 2009 as a fusion of the 20-year-old NatFilm Festival and the four-year-old CIFF.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] The CPH:PIX festival takes place in mid-April.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] CPH:DOX is Copenhagen's international documentary film festival, every year in November.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] In addition to a documentary film programme of over 100 films, CPH:DOX includes a wide event programme with dozens of events, concerts, exhibitions and parties all over town.
[src:copenhagen/copenhagen-p02] While honorary citizenship is no longer granted in Copenhagen, three people have been awarded the title of honorary Copenhageners (*æreskøbenhavnere*).
